node.text: Urgent! 🚨 2116 Willemore is set to be demolished tomorrow. No amount of discussion was going to change the owner's mind and legally, there was nothing the "Friends of the Original Leland Farmhouse" could do to save it. Here are my pictures from the final walk-through today before demolition.  Cinda Klickna took notes for her upcoming article in the Illinois Times. Here are some pictures Theresa O’Hare took of the "eyesore" (Frank’s words, I’m sure), via a Facebook post of hers. We are disgusted to learn that the current owner, a Mr. Frank Vala, chair of the Springfield Airport Authority, has refused salvage of anything in the incredible interior. 😡 He should be ashamed!! We JUST learned of this today! Anyone of our followers have any pull to prevent this to be demolished without being salvaged first?? 🥺 @savingoldhouses @cheapoldhouses @lelandgroveillinois #thisplacematters #historicpreservation #deserve2preserve

Another #mansardmonday goodie! 💜 Posted @withregram • @seaofsteps Happy Mansard Monday, old house lovers! With all the gardens in full bloom right now, it feels as though all of my favorite houses are wearing their finest jewelry. I love winter—you can see more of the house when the leaves have fallen!—but you just can’t beat riotous summer flowers.

node.text:
Happy #mansardmonday 🖤 Posted @withregram • @oldnewenglandhouses ○●○● The Tamworth Inn (ca. pre-1888), Tamworth, New Hampshire. ○●○●

In the 19th century, the farming village of Tamworth industrialized the Swift river with mills and machine manufacturing. While these developments employed many, the town was destined by the end of the century to provide a quiet summer retreat for travelers, like president Grover Cleveland. A man and mill owner Arthur E. Higgins expanded his own home, adjacent to the old Town meetinghouse, purchased and adjoined a neighboring gothic revival cottage, and built a further expansion to both, in opening the new Tamworth Inn in 1888. Since the 1830s, some lodging had existed on the site, possibly in the old core of the second empire style house shown, or in the (now demolished) smaller gothic cottage once beside it. This building, with its gentle mansard roof, central square pyramidal tower, recreated front porch, trim and trusses, corner pillasters, and pedimented dormer windows, was recently restored to its early 20th century appearance, save that the nearly 20 room additions to the east have been demolished; in their place, a modern distillery opened (tamworthdistilling) that relies on yields from its own adjacent gardens, and local farms. 

■□■□■□■□■□■□■□■□■□■□■

node.text:
"Why not?" Wednesday
Anyone one else have a house that "sinks into your soul?"
Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie 
Reposted from @sharon_heyward_art No musical or witty caption today. I just felt like sharing with you in my own voice a feeling I had earlier. I happened to pass by this gem today and had to pull over. I had no intention on stopping, I've already snapped it a couple of times. But I am so very much drawn to this house. I absolutely adore it. Sometimes certain houses I shoot sink into my soul. This one definitely has. It makes me feel something deeply. I can't explain exactly what I feel when I see it, but it's a pleasant mixture of thoughts and feelings. It just makes me feel good. Real good. I want to hold on to that feeling longer so I snap a pic and look at it from time to time. Not quite the same as standing in front of it like I did today admiring it. But this place really and truly moves me. Takes me to a place. I love when that happens. I do. -- 🙂✌🏽 #oldhousecharm #oldhouselove #secondempire @mansardmonday
